The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", a pamphlet has been published.
In Burkina Faso, women declared witches have common traits.
They tend to belong to the older generation, cannot work for example for health reasons, are free and have no children.
The one who becomes a "witch" is isolated so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"Man very rarely has this destiny."
"Young women are also not judged to be healthy because they participate in labour and give birth to children," says a sister who cares in the West African capital, Burkina Faso, in a special facility of more than 100 women who have been rejected by society.
The local government decided to intervene against this unusual "social measure".
He has published a pamphlet that should help limit witch hunting.
The case has a "catch".
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the daily Die Standard warned about the disadvantage of written education.
The accusation of witchcraft is common in other African countries.
In Burkina Faso's neighbour Ghana, Ammy Hemma, a 72-year-old woman, died after being tortured by three women and a man and then burned with oil they had sprayed on her.
It was the BBC server that transmitted this information.
The criminals claim it was the evil eye.
According to their version, the oil used for ritual anointing ignited on contact with the woman.
The oil blazed, it seems, when the team wanted to "chase away the evil spirit" of the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is approved by people of all levels of education.
The daily Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Human spirit eaters have always been a danger," he said.
While Burkina Faso is working to curb the witch hunt, Gambia as recently as last year even saw the President himself participate.
"Gambian President Dzammi, after the death of his aunt, launched a broad witch hunt who, it seems, participated in his death and tried with black magic to kill the President as well."
"Shamans from nearby Guinea came to the rescue, brought to the presidential farm in Kanilai, under the protection of police and the personal guard of the President, men and women chosen at random from villages in The Gambia," Amnesty International said in a message.
On the farm the imprisoned people had to drink a plant-based potion with hallucinogenic effects that also caused other effects on the kidneys and intestines.
Two prisoners did not survive.
Under international pressure, about a thousand people were released.
Bakal's tenant: The stoves are heating up, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man walked out the door of the customer center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He carried under his arm a file with three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating runs on solid fuel," points to the man who has the signing power on his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway," he explains angrily and half-resigned.
The citizens' association of BytyOKD.cz apartments, which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a wave of the hand.
"One says that, the other says something else," frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesdays at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a guard from a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You do not have time to read your number "157" that your number already begins to light up on the big screen under the topit of the waiting room.
In a split second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents don't seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
The majority of people came to solve common problems like everywhere - requests for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving letters with new lease agreements in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," replies, after a moment's hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the customer introduces himself as a journalist.
Deragulation and the former miners' apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
Lubomir Zaoralek, deputy speaker of parliament from the Ostrava region, of the Social Democrats, reported on this quite extensively before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change me a put... n of board in the toilet, relieves himself in introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to be sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as RPG promised in a special offer.
It is a rebate of half the amount of rent that will receive the other loctaries who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is really not burdened by questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent," says the employee at the counter.
And yet RPG offers both on its website and in the windows individual interviews on rents when necessary.
If the two parties do not agree on the rent, an independent tribunal will make the decision.
"These are not threats but only to inform about the unique and legitimate way to act legally," RPG says on its website.
"No one will go to court here," thinks one of RPG Byty's employees and the man in the street in front of the customer center agrees with her.
"I have 13,000 crowns of pension and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court," he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore people wait," she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," says Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the rent increase.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able with rents to invest in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 it should make 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
"The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be no more than 7.50 Czech crowns per m² per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase is for only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, it is an increase of a really very low sum of 19.66 Czech crowns per m²," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical increase but a gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices understood by the architects.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - colored walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch. design employees have been able to go there.
The architectonic project company Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini company nursery school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
She employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and it was important to her that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
Along with short-time employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by Arch. Design. as part of its social programme.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine work taking care of children.
These are the employees of Arch. Design.themselves who imagined this nursery school and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-kindergarten is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme for Human Resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to funding grants (up to 2.8 mil.de Czech crowns). They were able to buy equipment and appliances and after two years ensure qualified personnel as well as start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini nursery school on its own funds.
The preparation of the project took a year and Economy rating helped to apply for the endowment.
The care of the children is provided by qualified staff, all day a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children. Children can go to nursery school without age limit, but they are over three years old for the most part.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school regardless of hierarchical position.
Although it is an individual care and education, the curriculum of the mini-kindergarten is comparable to that for preschool education.
The children not only play but also quality education is provided - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not have the stress of being late in picking up children from a school far from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.has thus registered among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly towards the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look into Gaudi's interiors.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase looks like a dinosaur spine and the balconies look like open fish mouths.
This is how the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi is.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the locals the nickname of Bone House.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, pleasant colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought with precision.
At night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brilliance of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of shapes also appears in interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyepiece and the slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at the number. 43, was born from the construction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction was done for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one but soon accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-unit house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for a representative apartment of the owner of the building and the use of mosaic for the facade were born.
For the façade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila house and Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the hot house right after it was finished because of its organic forms "the Bone House".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the house that yawns".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi has designed for the house a unique system in its time of central heating, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the building guidelines of the time and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finishing the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
It did not please, for example, the members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction encroached on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) the authorization to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled out by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of linking spaces.
The common area can be connected completely by opening the doors of the lounges and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received besides new facades a non-traditional roof and two floors more.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with skylights.
The two-color play gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark which on the contrary absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Battlo house, which was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the visits because they found that it is a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to the common areas and the attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; Students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders get 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance fee to Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you need to quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and completely visit the house.
How to choose a mattress and box spring: women have different criteria than men.
No ostentatious setting, but rather the quality of the bedtime area, so the mattress and box spring give a real base for a good bed.
They must of course complement each other harmoniously to please a concrete user.
During the choice several things are decisive: weight, height, age, state of health as well as the sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and box spring will be placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in the country house where one does not sleep continuously latex mattresses are not suitable because they "warm up" gently.
They also weigh more than standard polyurethane mattresses.
It is necessary to turn them frequently.
If they do not also have enough ventilation channels in the core and if they remain, in addition, on a solid board, they retain moisture. Mold can also form there.
Habit is also decisive in the choice.
Those who spend most of the time abroad where very thick mattresses with a softening layer are frequently used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
"That's how all the hokeyists who come back from the NHL complain that they can't sleep there."
"For their tired shoulders, feet and ribs, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam."
"Such mattresses are also recommended for people who suffer from diabetes who have a nervous system disorder that therefore poorly assume 'information' from joints and skin," says Sylva Adamczikova who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That's why a few years ago the mattress with lazy foam conquered hokeyists as well as other customers.
"Today everything is going well, Tempur, the Italian Magnifex but also the Czech Tropico have for example suitable mattresses.
You don't have to be an NHL guy to enjoy a lazy foam.
This "miracle" simply works.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the heat absorbed or adapts to the heat of your body.
Nothing puts pressure on you and you won't turn around in the night like after a tough game.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also works as a protection against esquarres.
For the choice of mattress according to your size, add the length of the feet, about 21/34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of 180cm therefore need a bed of 210/220 cm.
The minimum width for each for a double bed should be 90 cm, i.e. a total of 180 cm.
For single-seater beds, singles for example, it is recommended to take at least 120 /140 cm.
This is convenient in case of visit.
'However there is a simple rule for the width of the bed: when lying on your back you should put your hands comfortably with your elbows slightly bent. Helena Prokopova, President of the Association of Saddlers-Mattressers and Decorators who has been dedicated for several years to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and teaches it in specialized schools.
For a double bed everyone needs their own box spring and mattress, so be careful however during the achât to choose the height of the mattress.
Otherwise you will only have to mount the box spring at different heights and this is not feasible on all bed frames.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, spring mattresses at least 15 cm, from this count for the shape and ventilation layer at least three centimeters.
"When touching or sitting on the mattress you should not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopova.
Each mattress requires a specific type of box spring.
The box spring bed, when the mattress and the box spring are united like Siamese sisters, has nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses ventilate very poorly; It should not be washed, which is common today.
And since during the night we normally sweat from 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat it is clear that after 5/7 years, the mattress begins to recall a large (and clogged) sieve.
For this, specialists refuse to advertise a 25-year lifetime for a mattress or a lifetime warranty.
But everything to its but.
And for this an advice of experience from the sellers: for a mattress of 120/140cm, forgo, for the coating of the mattress, hygiene or washing but rather add a protective mattress that you can easily remove and wash.
And even if nowadays it is common to make coatings with zipper for the whole set, that is to say that after opening we have two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine it is very important!) otherwise the manipulation for large models (and for only one person) becomes when they are removed a fight between a light weight and a heavy weight in a ring.
Do you have a rigid board in your bed instead of a box spring?
Never!
Maximum for a bed intended for visitors for a single night.
However equip the board (if there are none) with ventilation holes and use the spring mattress with a minimum height of 15cm with pouch springs (from Germany Taschenfederken) and a layer of ventilation.
A polyurethane mattress should not be part of a bed of this type.
For single-position slat bases with 14/18 slats, latex mattresses or so-called sandwiches (perhaps the combination of latex and coconut), are ideal but it will always be better for you to have a mattress with more slats, 28 and above, where the lamellae are lined in the lower part of the kidneys and it is thus possible to regulate their rigidity.
For multi-position mattresses do not take a spring mattress because it does not respond to changes in position.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the lamellae, you can also install what is called a shoulder cradle.
It is a special connection of the lamellae that allows to put pressure or even tilt the lamella so that the shoulder of the sleeper "integrates" well.
For men who have "shoulders as wide as their backs", this is really an important thing.
This thing is already considered by mattress manufacturers who for "men" have begun to use a softening area at the shoulders.
But they also think about women - they again offer them a softer surface at the hips.
For the most difficult customer there are wing or platelet bed bases with what is called a multi-force suspension.
The pressure spreads to more points and diinuates the tension.
But of course, be careful, as soon as you use a bad pillow (large and inflated with air) on good mattresses and box spring, the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is a simple pillow: the pillow should support the head, and its tips should reach only the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can rest.
The recommended size is 50X60 cm that Scandinavians for example prefer.
When lying on your side, the pillow should level (with the shoulder cradle of the box spring or the softened area in the mattress) the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses still have something in common with the first ones based on straw and herbs.
Manufacturers still use natural materials or mixtures.
The trend is also towards organic mattresses.
The petrole-based raw materials, from which polyurethane is made, are replaced by natural oils, such as soybean oil.
Almost all known manufacturers use soy.
"The term organic for mattresses means that the heart is made from natural products," says Petr vasicek of the company Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used for mattress coverings; One of the first was aloe vera.
But you can add micro-capsules that develop forest or lavender scents.
There are differences between men and women.
While birch plant extract so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, "cools" the man, coatings "heat" women.
Red pepper extract accelerates blood circulation and is therefore warmer for the weaker sex.
The current favorites?
Mattresses made from cold foam (it has more pores with a disturbed cell structure so more breathable than standard polyurethane and has more elasticity.
The combination of different stiffness of cold foams results in polyzone mattresses that know precisely where the head, lower back and feet are.
You will pay for a quality mattress from 7000 crowns and more.
Those that are characterized by their parameters for health have less VAT and are taken as instruments for health.
In the Czech Republic, Gumotex reached first place.
Saving for the mattress and box spring is not easy.
From time to time, it is possible to have two mattresses for the price of one as part of special actions on the part of manufacturers or producers.
For example, the company Magniflex offers Duofreeze mattresses with Memory memory foam sewn to the coating for 11990 crowns.
We can obviously take the second one for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and great thickness was started with Tempur material at a "cosmic" pace.
It started as material for NASA because astronauts were experiencing huge load factors at the start.
The Tempur softens in the heat and hardens, on the contrary, in the cold.
It therefore adapts perfectly to the hot human body and distributes optimal pressure.
It is therefore ideal against poor sleep and for an increase in comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses but also for health products, such as special foot cushions that relieve the legs and venous system.
Czech manufacturers use, for example, EucathermC or Twinsaver foam or the same type.
Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can just as easily be used to trace the movement of people and help in certain cases such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved many people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but just another way to reduce the likelihood that there will be another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to carry something like this, he will get rid of it.
"And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control."
"Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracing devices, have already brought parents to long waits," Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
"Right now, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will look for them too because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits that such devices can help during an unprepared assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracing services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The apparatus may be set in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, there is still the last position of the person concerned."
"More expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and finds themselves lying down without moving," says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special software.
The problem with current tracing systems is that they are either a device similar to those worn as a pendant the size of a matchbox or to the smallest telephone devices.
They can always be lost.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracing device."
"Or he will find out after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
It is a combination of GPS location acquisition systems (which is commonly used in autonavigation) and a mobile phone feature that alerts a vehicle's current position.
The army has so many explosive cords that it could go around the Czech Republic with it. But it can only last two years.
The army has purchased 445 km of ropes used for explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense had bought 224 km.
