At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public competition
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handcuffed the local entrepreneur and real estate trader Lubos. G.
The latter had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a claim for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a particular candidate.
The latter had to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"For now I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in a public tender and competition." said for the newspaper Pravo the head of the prosecutor's office of Plzen Antonie Zelena, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
As to how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in view of the so little official information.
In response to a question from Pravo, Land Fund spokeswoman Lubomira Cerna said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"This was a customer and not an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has the real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Law" and is set up when several candidates who benefit from rights come forward.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to resitutions which must be settled before the value of the land is announced".
"According to the proposed rights a ranking of the purchasers is put in place and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," explained the spokesman of the Fund.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the call and as he himself is also a beneficiary because having purchased a large number of rights to restitutions, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in by withdrawing.
This would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
It was included in the case of the former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted in criminal proceedings for having published land for which the decision to set up a building had already been published.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in place where the access artery to the Borske Pole industrial estate was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far higher.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked jeopardizing the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an extra 100 crowns monthly for housing.
Households from January will have to pay extra not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
From January, families will therefore have to draw from their wallets up to a hundred crowns monthly more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity for apartment households is expected to be around 100 crowns more than at present.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the significant development to encourage the manufacture of renewable energies, especially photovoltaic cells.
Gas increases moderately but of course when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
We can therefore also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 crowns more per month, families in Libérec will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For Prague residents is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If rents do not change the people of Prague will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are rising by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase significantly for example in the 450 thousand rental apartments from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase it up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new rent increase will be taken to court by the company.
The regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from the parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for recurrence are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of physicians who encounter cases similar to admissions from children's departments in hospitals.
"Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk."
"The trend is really towards strong alcohol," says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the hospital in Horovice in Central Bohemia.
"When they manage to steal a bottle from the cupboard, it is sometimes wisky but it is fernet and vodka that prevail."
"Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it," says the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for the Motel Hospital, also agrees with him.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"It's now the fashionable alcohol, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from home," Jurinova added.
According to Department Chief Pélikan, seeing drunk children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide area completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized four times.
"She began her career at the age of twelve when she was brought with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood with the addition of a mixture with ecstasy," described the doctor.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Centre at a party."
"What is interesting is that it did not seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent 48 hours," says the Director of the Department astonished.
It is precisely the disinterest of parents or their extraordinary tolerance in the face of the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we mean a chronic dependence on alcohol of several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that we do not find in children".
"In those who use the acool repeatedly, it is rather a socio-family back-ground significantly unfavorable," explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police, are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, there are three seasonal waves to which we can reck: Witches' Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced on Witches' Day an admission of 7 drunk children all at once," Pelikan said.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have a great evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them."
"They are only amazed at where they are," adds Pelikan, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care bed hospitalization can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay back a single evening," Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their declining management, which should recover from parents the costs related to care, do not deal with cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 aircraft of the five in all, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport planes, took off Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is headquartered.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of anyone other than the Czech army.
Yet they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seat versions of the L-159T1 that were until now in service with the Czech Army and were airworthy.
The three remaining aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Press Department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical departure of the Vodochody planes is currently unknown.
"The single-seat L-159 aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from aircraft that had been stored for a long time without causing additional burdens or investments for the Ministry of Defense."
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters were exchanged in the state," Pejsek told Pravo.
He added that the army will not remain without a two-seater since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The military took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS is committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of some Allied countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore a matter for whoever takes into account how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for one Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by Mirek Topomanek's government.
The Ministry of Defence did not issue a call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
the Directorate of Defence argued that the exchange ensured a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and uses only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
however, the European Commission has lodged a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen as part of an EU-wide tender and under no circumstances by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index finger longer than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than their ring finger are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before the age of 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors like family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of their right hand shorter than their ring fingers.
For them, as for the 19 per cent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index finger longer than the ring finger the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before 60 years the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but that it does not seem to him, it seems, that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "fully demonstrated".
