The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was a great success and attracted visitors from all over the world.
There are also special chocolate ice cream courses spanning several days. Similarly, practical sessions are organized in the private ice cream shop.
In the midst of a midlife crisis, a number of people dream of a new career, others simply venture to fulfill their burning desire on smooth ice.
This time, 40 participants came from 19 countries on all continents, from Brazil to Saudi Arabia and Hungary.
Jacky, an art education teacher from California, is passionate about the Slow Food movement. In the future, he wants to offer a quality European product in the land of industrial ice.
Anke from Berlin is a business consultant and after a few years she wants to get something unique out of this nerve-wracking job.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening an ice cream shop in Cairo.
A man from Malta and another from Brazil would like to improve the quality of ice cream in their bars, and the Canadian housekeeper came because her kids love Italian ice cream.
Master ice cream maker Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of perfect ice cream.
Determining is not only the good flavor, but also the silky suppleness and consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during the training the icing on the cake of the national and, in general, southern superstructure: "Italian ice cream is simply the best: and then it still retains a sacred dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large blender that heats everything to 85 degrees through an electronic program, then immediately cools to four degrees.
He then opens a tap installed on the machine: he takes out a white cream of pasteurized base, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately assailed with questions: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can we give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr. Luciano warns against being misled by the spirit of the times.
Anyone who only talks about ice cream "made from natural ingredients", may have nevertheless used stabilizers: most often a natural product, for example, guar seed flour obtained from guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using a stabilizer, only it must be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will bite nothing but ice pellets.
Some modifications to the base mass are permitted.
It gets more exciting with the aromas.
Master Luciano establishes the difference between the ingredients that are acquired in the fruit or confectionery section of the supermarket.
In addition, there are powder and pasta.
"Suppliers will all try to pass dozens of flavored ingredients back to you."
"However, you should just try."
Either in the recipes of fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
Or in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs, becomes a yellow cream and constitutes, when cocoa powder is added, the basis of all possible chocolate desserts.
Now all course participants must switch to the use of ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the basic mass, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural ingredients.
Different kinds of fruit ice cream are also subjected to the same experiment.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of nuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The popular kiwi ice cream is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
"Only a balanced mixture correctly enhances the taste of an ice cream," says Luciano.
Making ice cream is a calculation exercise: if peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the amount of sugar must be reduced in the basic recipe.
A sugar supplement is required for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents a device with which he determines the sugar content of different types of fruit (winemakers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, tables make calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires, as in the past, as much physical intervention.
It's not just the automatic base mass manufacturing machine that helps.
There is also a device in which the available ice mixture is simultaneously beaten to make it creamy and brought back to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
Brazil's Gustavo smears fruit puree from head to toe and splashes his classmates when control of the colossal mixing bowl eludes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that "such an incident is likely to occur during every class: it is only a matter of time."
