The latter is financed by groups such as Monsanto, Nestlé or Bayer.
Kuiper was instrumental in developing EFSA's testing requirements for genetically modified plants and is therefore clearly in a conflict of interest, according to Then's criticism.
The regulations drawn up correspond verbatim, in paragraphs, to the positions adopted by the pressure group Ilsi and thus bear the mark of the industry which, basically, is controlled by the authorities based in Parma, Italy.
This is already the second time that Testbiotech has denounced a conflict of interest.
A senior EFSA official recently joined the Swiss food group Syngenta unconditionally or without a transitional period. In doing so, She changed sides.
Not long ago, even Central German Radio (Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk, MDR) revealed the existence of personal relations between the European Union supervisory authority and the industrial lobby, which aroused the suspicions of both the German Federal Environment Agency and MEPs.
However, EFSA does not accept the existence of any conflict of interest.
One opinion indicates that all reliable data, including industry data, is used as long as it is of good professional quality.
Experts working on behalf of EFSA are not prohibited from establishing contacts with this sector of activity.
But they should make them public.
Kuiper admits he works for the US-based International Life Sciences Institute (ILSI).
This body sees itself as a neutral forum bringing together experts from the fields of science, industry and policy and others to assess the risks of biotechnology without being in the pay of a lobby.
