The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications of a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of 5-6 September 2007 at around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It lies on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
His name appears in IAEA documents because it refers to the reactor that Syria has built apparently with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a briefing by the United States intelligence services, the CIA, dating from late April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well suited to produce plutonium, which would make it possible to manufacture atomic weapons.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring blurry satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each reactor component before the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the interior of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be commissioned, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is little more information than then, and even, with time, the mystery thickens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor at el-Kibar, but had little evidence that Syria was developing "an active nuclear weapons program."
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of an "alleged reactor", even if they consider the CIA's presentation "plausible".
They lack hard evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he ensures he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior UN diplomat gave only a terse answer in the summer, saying the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions."
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble of the "unused military building" and proceeded to methodically level the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts, led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen, discovered traces of man-made uranium in el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA received satellite images from commercial contractors from a member State showing the moment directly following the attack. it seems that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, possibly Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always maintained that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after the analysis of the particles as implausible.
Since then, Damascus has refused to discuss this, as well as satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to carry out a second inspection at the el-Kibar site and refuses access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then sitting prime minister at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
Thus, the investigation into this case has dragged on since June 2008 without reaching a result and "is increasingly turning into a serious problem of the Agency's credibility", as a senior Western diplomat serving at IAEA headquarters in Vienna acknowledges, ultimately it is a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA considers that in order to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have a "functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities are involved, what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah respectively also from the names of neighboring cities.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington identified these locations and found on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that is most likely one of the suspicious objects.
It is possible that it is in a military base or directly next to it; that is exactly why Syria is denying IAEA inspectors access to the three sites.
In Vienna, it is claimed that the Syrians fear that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it is intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that attracts the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could "be used for fuel production."
It would have "no indications of sensitive activities", such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are indispensable for the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works on unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses about the following fundamental questions: where should the uranium have come from and where the plutonium needed to make the bomb would later have been separated.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide valuable traces, was stored at the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with earth are gone, no one will have any information about where the rubble is stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located only a few kilometers from el-Kibar, on the other side of the Euphrates River, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for the storage of radioactive waste.
By recently analyzing satellite photos taken for the famous Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley linked them to the reactor in question.
Satellite photos, however, show that Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspect sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those locations.
It is possible that this was a coincidence, but it did not help to dispel suspicions.
In diplomatic circles, it is said that the IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for inspections to be carried out there. This plan was to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows how interested the inspectors are in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also ignored this proposal.
A year ago, if Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported on the destruction of the reactor, the urgency would not be reported for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the US ambassador who has been talking for some months about what is known as special inspections, one of the most powerful means the Atomic Agency has to implement its controls.
