The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the US in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro poll taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it tracks attitudinal changes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the fairly sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy recovered after suffering a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are staunch democrats, pushing down the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; This is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Figure 3).
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, both the same as last year; but up sharply compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shook support for democracy.
If this held up during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in the Americas suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, to 32 percent.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Figure 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widely shared sense of progress.
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
This is only the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
