An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a truly 'foreign' form of life," said Paul Davies C.W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in California's Mono Lake, is able to continue growing after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"One wonders what's still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms might be able to use other elements to activate biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed," commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes.  United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cogelll added.
This was not a serendipitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; Thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute one for the other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, agencies have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
"But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and, in a way, erases the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; But nothing has ever shown that it can work.
Arsenic was more common early in Earth's existence, she says; Thus, the researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
