Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have dropped criminal charges against Sen. John Ensign stemming from a case related to a former campaign aide and his efforts to get lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible 2012 Republican presidential candidate until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Ensign's office said it was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be subject to disciplinary action by the Senate ethics committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer under investigation and did not intend to pursue any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice declined to comment.
The announcement came as something of a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, secure lucrative lobbying work to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then advocated for their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an associate of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual deal between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to contradict the so-called revolving door ban on lobbying.
Based on the evidence that has been made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of conspiracy to violate and material violation of the Revolving Door Law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
While the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning behind the Ensign decision, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop charges against former Sen. Ted Stevens accused of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the executive director of citizens for accountability and ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that has received several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Ensign's legal team had been working with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutor's office.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Committee decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is one for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him he was "hammering" the Interior Department on an issue in dispute.
Ensign also attended a luncheon with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the transportation secretary to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth-largest Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Department of Justice's lead and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing her hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
