Can civility bridge divides?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a modicum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of true bipartisan forward cooperation or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan fighting in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the "lame duck" session.
But clearly, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points. Empty scoring point partisan.
Wednesday's public meeting of the president's deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but which, nevertheless, still divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That's why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxation, expenses, health care, or entitlements, the two sides stay miles apart.
Yet the November election moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no question that things have changed in tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now stands alongside the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then fade.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve part or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the "lame duck" session, with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the lame duck session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done are, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea who helped create it.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the Deficit Committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their own view, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group; This suggests that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; and then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully watch the public reaction.
Whoever is judged to be losing will have to change course and find compromises.
But it would nevertheless be an optimistic point of view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility on display this week might be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked US documents describe Moscow as a haven for corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "kleptocracy" and is smuggling some of the bribes and protective money it collects to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia said in a February memo.
The police and the Federal Security Service carry out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized crime groups.
Every layer of the bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" – is doing its part as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The note is based on redacted sources.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and it is largely held accountable for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little sign of cleaning up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Baturina, who owns a leading construction company, have consistently denied accusations of corruption over the years; And he has won several defamation lawsuits on those charges.
In September, he told a Russian television station, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's to be thrown away, it's nonsense."
Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt; according to surveys.
But it is unusual to find the information stated in an embassy report; And it is unheard of to conceive that it would be up to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it 'dysfunctional' and claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government," according to the embassy note.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term used in the criminal/mafia world that literally means 'roof' or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-level structure in Moscow's criminal underworld."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, MVD and militias are on the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a void in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services."
The report states that the FSB handles the money of the largest companies and that the police target the small ones.
One source, he said, "explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is better to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law."
"This is why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer as high."
