"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They are suspicious because they don't know exactly how many people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful atrait here.
In the heights of the Dangrek mountains, a path, overgrown with weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty tin roof.
