Red Bull triumphs in F1 with secret weapon from Siemens
Software creates improvements on cars in real time.
As soon as Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select world of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first, no one took into account the options of a new team that had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the past November, in the last phase of the championship they all bet on the triumph of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without lowering the ability as a driver of the champion, the German Sebastien Vette, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 we talk about the legend of the "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives far removed from high motorist competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to create assembly lines for manufacturing plants around the world, energy stations, high-precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory allowed Red Bull to create and execute "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and tests.
Russwurm explains that the 1992 teams had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on the vehicles each season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyse and project all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull's cars except the engine, which is the exclusive responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can go from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced high-tech laser and autoclave production systems.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological improvement is the amount of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend as a limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to create and produce its cars in a locality 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret".
The staff for this duty is 580 people, including two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's Formula 1 hero, arguably, is recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Between the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other hidden protagonists, whose activity is invaluable and whose notoriety is zero.
The plant's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be argued that R+D advances in the case of race cars brought 50% of the wins and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and technology accounts for 85% of success, while pilots provide 15% of the added value.
Nevey admits that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computers, because "they are unpredictable gladiators".
