"I think that most of the mergers have been carried out, we cannot say that the incorporation of Cajasol into the Banca Cívica group is a second phase, these are adjustments."
"Most of it was done completely; it is possible that instead of 17 we will go to 13 or 14, but all the major processes have already been carried out under the supervision of the Bank of Spain, which has collaborated a lot in this operation too," said the leader.
In statements during a breakfast of the Association of Leaders and Executives of Aragón (ADEA), Olavarrieta explained that the process of concentration is being carried out "at the highest possible speed and we must be very satisfied with the way it is carried out within the deadlines that have been set in the past, not now, in the business plans with the Bank of Spain",  he emphatized.
"The move from 45 funds with an average of 28,500 million in asset volume to 17 with 75,500 million is a trial without parallel in history, reducing the number of entities by 62% so that they are much larger to be Basel compliant," he said.
Olavarrieta acknowledged that "there is a series of rather unhappy opinions about the slowness of the process" that demonstrate "a lack of serosity and meaning", because "what the Bank of Spain is doing is reminding us that we must respect the deadline before the end of the year".
The director general of the ECSC, José Antonio Olavarrieta, assured yesterday that Spain has the most rigorous financial system in all of Europe and "probably" in the world and he attributed to those who question it a "lack of knowledge".
The leader mentioned that given the current economic situation, "we can remain very quiet" with the situation of financial entities and savings banks, a system that has begun a process of concentration "very important" and "is going at the greatest possible speed".
He also recalled that the Spanish banking sector has done well from the stress tests that ECB carried out in July.
Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin opted to stay in the euro, but it set the conditions for the whole Union.
Market tensions provoked a doble government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero announced new adjustment methods, which vary from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private employment agencies or abolition of the 426 euros of aid to the unemployed without professional contribution to the privatization of the 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and the 30% of the State Lotteries.
On the other, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins Chancellor Angela Merkel's criticism of her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another restriction of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the currency zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, even if now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, nearly 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments by one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first signal of divergence between what Germany thought should be done (fiscal austerity plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including the France, were practicing.
The second blow of the Central European country was when Merkel hardly prolonged the decision to save Greece.
From that moment it was fiercely criticized, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union's treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time force private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat watered down, was approved and, in the following months, we should see the process of reforming the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not be too much in agreement, from that date on the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new currency area, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they can be forced to declare themselves in default and, in this case, the private sector will also bear part of the costs.
Germany warns us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high rates of savings and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge balance-of-payments holes, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The stakes are clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of renewing the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What is being asked of us is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence allows us to achieve greater tranquility.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double declaration (the reforms promised after the last Saturday's meeting with big business and yesterday's announcement of the new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the way has been opened to the thesis that the house must be put in order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities that are envisaged, we cannot exclude that of abandoning a monetary zone too full of unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it warned us.
Sport and Fraud of the Law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion plotted in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused a lot of ink to flow on the unsporting nature of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, a few minutes before finishing the match (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately wasted time when they committed fouls to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will end up being leaders of their group, both players will carry out the regulatory sanction during the next match of the play-off match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned the team's coach, Jose Mourinho, with two games and different economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen in this case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization,  it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated story of a histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the rules contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are committing a fraud of the law; Because, indeed, they are respectful actions with the sporting regulations, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to look at the kind of harm they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the goods that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these goods alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the team of infringer players from taking unfair advantage of the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out secretly to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders gain from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not obtain an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action supposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club wouldn't be able to rely on those players.
Obviously the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players perform a penalty match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So that, climbing the ladder, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to sportsmanship, which includes strategic decision-making that maximizes the benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not take action to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), but otherwise they chose instead the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from it.
Even if the line between genius and fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as much ethical as aesthetic.
Offensive of offers to capture Christmas dinners for groups in BCN
The dictatorship of the calendar concentrates this year an avalanche of reservations for days 16 and 17.
There is a proliferation of self-funded celebrations by employees who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros.
Like the turret and the lottery, when December arrives also come the group dinners before Christmas that continue to be the oxygen balloon for restaurants and entertainment in Barcelona, but which because of the crisis have led to an offensive adjusted prices to be able to capture the majority customer: almost all want to spend between 20 and 30 euros on dinners or meals,  The businessmen and industry associations interviewed coincide.
