Pakistan's nuclear program is causing great concern in the United States
Islamabad is producing atomic weapons at "a faster rate than any other country."
Wikileaks leaks confirm the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department filtered by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concern caused in Washington by the Pakistani nuclear programme.
Apart from the enlightening and tasty details offered about the content of the conversations and thoughts of the US diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of atomic security, instead of increasing, is "decreasing" and that the volatile Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program – the fact that weapons are not assembled, but are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack – is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
Thus, the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report before the visit of former National Security Adviser, James Jones: "The proximity of certain nuclear facilities in the territory under Taliban attack, the dispersion of nuclear materials whose noise runs and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials".
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is viewed, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as a proliferation and a reason to maintain the guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the decline in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs," said expert Yuri Korolev of the Russian Ministry of External Affairs during a meeting with his American counterparts.
The news of the documentation filtered through Julian Assange's portal is the ever-shrinking cooperation between the US and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and Pakistan's high degree of nuclear arma production.
An embassy dispatch in May, which described communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", argued: "Transparency is frequently non-existent; offers of help remain unanswered or are eliminated."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, National Intelligence official for South Asia, noted that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the official that "the Pakistan Army must end with tacit support for terrorist groups."
Hunting for the head of Wikileaks
Obama will number a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further infiltrations.
Interpol issues a red alert to track movements and locate Assange.
All aspects related to Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, form a complicated labyrinth where it is difficult to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red alert" to "locate and track the movements" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest order.
In addition, this one is not new, otherwise it dates from November 20.
And this one has nothing to do with the latest filtration of more than a quarter million diplomatic documents from the United States but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer and creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange".
On the 20th the international police force based in Lyon (France) dictated the order at the request of Sweden, but it did not make it public until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
Thus, all 188 Interpol countries were instructed to identify or locate Assange "to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition."
Even if Interpol cannot issue an order for the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization, consider the red notice call a clear avenue for arrest - which the national police force must carry out - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England.  where Assange is believed to be.
The move outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing the fact that the 39-year-old Wikileaks founder has shown himself willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange applied for and obtained the permit to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, who is compared to the notorious Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's security chief.
"This appears to be a hunt, not a legal persecution," the letter said.
While the world searches for him – and in Australia his mother defends her son's innocence – Assange continues to be in an unknown place, but he is not silent.
On Monday he gave an interview to the editor of Time magazine through Skype at an undetermined location, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that she was responsible for giving orders to the American graduates they spy on at the UN by violating the international treaties that the United States signed, she should resign," he said.
His opinion was insulted yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd."
"I'm not at all sure why the opinion of a guy with a web page should interest us," he told CNN.
Obama himself tasked a senior counterterrorism official, Rusell Travers, with preventing further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama's spokesman's attempt to downplay Assange's importance contrasts with the views conservative politicians and commentators are proclaiming these days.
Peter King, the congressman who from January will chair the National Security Committee in the lower house, has asked the State Department to study the possibility of including Wikileaks in the list of terrorist organizations "to confiscate its funds and prosecute anyone who provides them with contributions or assistance".
Even further went Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who had to retract his statements after saying Assange should "be assassinated."
"Obama should turn it into a target and wear out an unmanned aircraft or something similar."
One person who did not ask for an apology was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible presidential candidate.
"Whoever is in the Government that leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything that is not an execution would be too kind a punishment," he told Fox.
