China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of this country in COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the trace of coal and detailed that it maintains its offer to reduce until 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its greenhouse gas emissions.
China stands by its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the trace of coal and reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
Nevertheless, he made it clear that China will not change its goals, but it will continue to work together with the international community in this area.
He mentioned that China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity-building; institution-building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all these areas, including the approval last year of a new Energy Law, which recognizes the objectives addressed with regard to the reduction of greenhouse gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with government and local authorities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, there are various multi-year plans underway or completed, both funded by the Chinese government and the governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned, the Energy Efficiency Program, which has been implemented for the past five years and has received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another for the change of incandescent lamps with energy-saving lamps and another for mitigation and adaptation, he detailed.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country's government's scientific adviser on climate change, said China's efforts have been greater than anyone thinks.
For example, he explained, China's per capita greenhouse gas emissions are three tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical contribution in contamination.
Similarly, it has made unprecedented efforts in the use of energy, how to increase a 20% energy efficiency in the last five years and plans to make another similar one around 2020, he said.
