President Barack Obama today joined the national mobilization to support the Dream Act, to legalize undocumented students, with a message on his personal Twitter account.
"If you agree with the approval of the Dream Act, call your senators and ask them to approve this legislation," Obama tweeted.
His short message keeps open a cyber link to a larger document that asks the public to contact senators immediately as the vote on legislation is imminent.
"With a vote that we hope soon, now is the time to listen to your voice," he said.
The message was leaked after the 42 Republican senators threatened to block the passage of any legislation if the extension of Bush-era tax cuts and government funding continues.
Such a blockage, announced in a letter signed by the 42 Republican senators, could affect the passage of the Dream Act and other projects such as the ratification of the New START Treaty with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
Asked about the Republican blockage of the Dream Act and other projects, presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said he is confident that once the tax problem is resolved we can fix an arrangement for the rest of the projects.
"I think we have a lot of time..."
"We all agree that this tax problem must be solved before the end of the year..."
"I think we can get an agreement at some point to that and then we can plan the sequence of the rest," he said.
Senate Democratic Majority Leader Harry Reid announced Tuesday that he would call for a "closing debate" vote on the Dream Act, which is why the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be voted on starting next Thursday in the Senate, although the most likely would be next week.
The Senate version of the Dream Act would legalize 800,000 young people who came to the United States before the age of 16, stayed in this country for the past five years and were accepted by an institution of higher learning or the military.
But supporters require 60 votes to approve the initiative, which is why they require the support of a large number of Republicans, at times when the project's partisan organizations are lobbying intensively to ensure the approval of the law.
The Democrats, the majority of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
Nevertheless, at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against it and only one Republican expressed support for the bill, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
That's why supporters of the Dream Act require the vote of several Republicans if other Democrats decide to vote against the initiative.
Among the most sought-after Republicans are Senators Maine, Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, and incumbent Senator George Lemieux of Florida, who completed Senator Mel Martínez's term.
Other Republicans who have supported the Dream Act in the past are Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but they have said they will not support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who supported him, John McCain, has not defined his posture so far.
Even though the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the biggest obstacles of the Dream Act are in the Senate.
With literature we put our finger on the wound
The second stage of the Pleasures of Language was a walk in which participants displayed the narrative
"Sex in language, I understand it, but... the finger on the wound? what do they expect from me?", asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela invited to open the second stage of the Pleasures of Language, a cycle that celebrates literature in Spanish and this time used the subtitle of her question (during another fair the round table was dedicated to Sex in the language, she explained).
The finger on the wound"... embarrasses us," the Argentine writer gently told the audience, most of them young people, who had gathered at the Guadalajara International Book Fair (FIL) to listen to this table moderated by Marisol Shultz and attended by Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García Montero.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio that Shultz defined afterwards as a great story, with Luisa in the first person as a protagonist who seeks to know what the "wound" is, she goes from one doctor to another, without getting an answer, only tracks in the same narrative thread.
From the infectiologist she comes out convinced: "patience is not my forte, it may be my wound".
At the end, after a frustrated approach with the traumatologist who took his breath away in the middle of the hallway, but who explains that wound is not a scientific term; It is the psychoanalyst who reveals the mystery: "The wound is what is open in reality, the symbolic is the scar".
The protagonist sighed relieved and concluded: "on the wound I could only know that it is that is open in reality and that it does not exist", but convinced of the fact that the pleasures and pitfalls of the language must be very intertwined.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both.
Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also exhibited a delightful narrative entitled In Praise of Invention, where the finger on the wound is not counted but at some point is discovered.
With touches of magical realism, he speaks of a famous bewitcher who touched clouds, made people who had gone far or repaired virtues that a damsel had lost, a narrative that turns to speak then America, the great news that had from the beginning its own chroniclers and quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo who criticizes the excesses of the narratives of the conquering captains.
"Cervantes, who invented all of us (writers), mocked the false witnesses who appeared in the stories presented as real, but in a different way one would never have told the history of America with an imagination that lacked even modesty."
Nevertheless, he stressed, "madmen and liars have the best imagination" and here reality converges with lies, we no longer know how much of the narrative belongs to one band or another, where fictional literature reaches its peak.
This is called the 'Cervantes tradition'.
"It is thanks to his legacy that we are what we tell."
In turn, writer Mayra Montyero annotated and applauded the variety of interpretations provoked by the invitation of the FIL with her round table The Must on the Wound.
The Cuban-Puerto Rican has put hers on the great plague of social violence that her country is going through - and Latin America shares - produces disputes over drug trafficking and sales.
"I think that good literature, good poetry and good songs contain a tacit commitment that is of course not premeditated," she said, after quoting that the reality of literature is the communication and the dimension of the commitment that is established between the author and the readers, and that it is a "chemical reaction" of the latter.
The evening ended with the intervention of the Spanish poet Luis García Montero who also stressed "it must on the wound of the committed writer".
He considered that in a world that lives in high speed also with regard to intellectual habits and the control of consciences that turns to the advantage of dogmatisms, "behind every statement there is a small no and behind every negation there is a small yes".
"To be the masters of our own feelings and be the masters of reality, we must nuance: and nuance means many times to put the finger on the wound and disturb people who feel very convenient thinking in caricature, in white and black, in established ideas and without nuance and also disturb the powers that prefer a world in white and black",  he said, inviting us to recover the meaning of writing.
Romano in the hunt for his first title
Rubén Omar Romano has had three defeats in finals he has had ups and downs in his career, but he has reached the decisive series three times.
With the duel of Santos Laguna and Monterrey in the final, there are also two different styles that confront each other, marked by their technicians, who find between them a contrast marked by the results.
Rubén Omar Romano has had three defeats in finals, he has had ups and downs in his career, but he has been able to reach the decisive series three times, even if so far he has not put in the mile and that's why this opportunity is very special for him.
The Argentinian ended up consoling himself with the sub-champion medal, he stayed one step behind the winners and curiously with the same team he played consecutive finals.
The Santist strategist reached his first final as a coach in the 2002 Opening Tournament, when he held the reins of Morelia with whom he lost with an overall result of 4-2 against Toluca; later, in the Closing 2003 he also arrived at the decisive duel and lost again with the overall result of 3-1 and it was precisely against Rayados.
With Santos Laguna already, in the Bicentennial Tournament 2010, again against the Diablos, Rubén suffered again a setback, as his team made a match tied 2-2 against the Choriceros after 210 minutes of play, but in the series of penalties he got an advantage for 3-1 with two opportunities to get the title and finally three of his players missed from 11 meters and he suffered the jumped to 4-3.
Rubén has lost two finals with the Diablos Rojos and one with Monterrey, his rival in the tournament, so he does not want to have the same fate, he tries to detach himself from the curse to be able to celebrate for the first time a title, even if he says that for him the institution is more important.
"I want to be champion, I don't want to break any statistics, this is for a club, not for a passion that I have and therefore I will get the title, but what I mentioned before is more important," said the helmsman when asked what his weaknesses would be in the finals.
He remembers a lot the last final, from which he assures that he learned a lot, "the only lesson we can learn is that until the referee whistles the final, we can not celebrate, we are prepared in the line, the players too, because last time, with two penalties to shoot we were already prepared to run and I believe that is a lesson,  Before the end of the game we can't celebrate."
He knows that this series could be defined by penalties, which does not worry him, because he confides in his players: "We never try to get to the series of penalties, we try to finish within the regular deadline, but sometimes we just have to prepare, the previous tournament we were prepared,  Unfortunately fate has taken a bad turn on us, sometimes it is the emotions or the anguish of holding the title in our hands, hands it escaped us, it served us as a lesson for this final and we hope that we do not arrive in this situation again".
Romano now has the opportunity to no longer be a sub-champion technician and taste for the first time the glory offered by the titles.
The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
Individuals should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; The cost The waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011 the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (CSAs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for aspirants, among which the following are mentioned:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for visa processing and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Persons who wish to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only go to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken from the CSA, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 service surcharge.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA to announce the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The US space agency has quoted the press to present tomorrow a discovery that will have an impact on the search for living beings in space.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States will communicate tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery, which could prove the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented in a press conference tomorrow Thursday at 1:00 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington for experts in astrobiology, the science that studies the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the Universe.
When it quoted the press, NASA assured that it would present who will have an impact on the search for extraterrestrial life," which has sparked speculation from experts in other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are creatures similar to us and in hostile environments that were thought to be uninhabited and would put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings like humans if its living conditions are improved.
There seems to be talk of a microbe discovered at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, which lives in an environment that was thought to be too venomous for any form of life, because the lake is rich in arsenic.
In any form, the creature uses arsenic as a way of life and this ability makes us think that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have our volunteer atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it proves that "there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know".
The space agency will communicate the true significance of the findings in tomorrow's press conference, Thursday.
The conference will feature geobiology by Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (Saturn's largest satellite), from the perspective that its chemistry is similar to that of Earth.
