14 suspected drug traffickers arrested
A dozen searches were carried out in Estrie on Wednesday, as part of the dismantling of a cannabis production and sales network.
Fourteen people have been arrested and will face various charges.
The searches took place in Sherbrooke, Orford and Stoke, mostly in places allegedly used for drug production.
"About 750 cannabis plants, four kilos of hashish, money and equipment used for production were seized," said Louis-Philippe Ruel, spokesman for the Sûreté du Québec.
In all, eleven men and three women were arrested, including the two alleged leaders of this network, two men from Sherbrooke.
Those arrested were to appear at the Sherbrooke courthouse within hours of their arrest.
They could face charges of cannabis production, possession for the purpose of trafficking, conspiracy and theft of services, among others.
The raids followed a lengthy investigation that lasted nearly a year.
"It was information received from the public that allowed us to make these arrests," Ruel said.
Some 70 police officers from the Estrie regional investigation module of the Sûreté du Québec, the Service de police de Sherbrooke and the Régie de police Memphrémagog took part in this police operation.
Irregular migration can continue without problems
The Conservatives' bill, which the government says should solve the problem of boats loaded with illegal migrants, will obviously be defeated while the three opposition parties indicated Wednesday that they could not support it.
"I rely heavily on the Charter."
"I'm standing with a party that created granite under your feet," Liberal Leader Michael Ignatieff said as he was surrounded by MPs after the weekly caucus meeting.
The Liberals claim that the bill as proposed, which would allow anyone from a ship identified as carrying illegal immigrants to be detained for up to a year, would violate the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
The leader of the Bloc Québécois, Gilles Duceppe, has also indicated that he cannot support the bill because he is attacking the wrong target.
"We are against it and it seems that all opposition parties are against it, so we will see what the government does," Duceppe said.
NDP immigration critic Olivia Chow dismissed criticism that her party is not tough enough on illegal immigrants.
"New Democrats agree that we should take action against human smugglers and that is what we are doing through another bill, Bill C-35," Chow said.
"We don't support the Conservatives' bill because it preys on refugees and imprisons children for at least a year," Chow said.
Immigration Minister Jason Kenney has accused opposition parties of playing politics and ignoring the will of Canadians.
"Canadians are telling MPs overwhelmingly that they do not tolerate this kind of illegal migration, these criminal operations that target Canada and treat the country like a doormat."
"They expect Canada to take strong action," Kenney said.
The government did not announce a vote of confidence on its bill, which could have led to an election if it was rejected.
However, a Conservative told QMI Agency that the government would ask for a vote so that each MP who opposes will then explain himself to his constituents.
The new unit is not unanimous
Despite the announcement of the possible creation of a permanent unit to fight corruption and collusion by Jean Charest, many observers continue to call for the creation of a public inquiry commission on the subject.
The Minister of Public Security, Robert Dutil, maintains that this idea is not new: Quebec would have consulted the Department of Investigation of New York on this subject as early as last January.
The metropolis has had a permanent unit on corruption since 1870.
Still, Tuesday's announcement came as a surprise to many.
It must be said that at a meeting of the Permanent Council on Police Services in Quebec on October 29, this measure was never discussed despite the presence of Robert Dutil.
It was enough for the PQ critic in public safety, Stéphane Bergeron, to describe this announcement as "rabbit out of a hat" and "solution cobbled together on the corner of a table".
Minister Dutil responded to those who fear that political power has too much influence on the possible future unity.
"You're going to see the result when we announce it," he said.
"We are aware of this problem."
For the president of the CSQ, Réjean Parent, nothing can replace the establishment of a public inquiry.
"The more Mr. Charest persists in not wanting to create this commission of inquiry, the more people think like you and me that he has something to hide," he said.
"The only way to have a commission of inquiry is the resignation of Jean Charest," said Yves Boisvert, professor of ethics and governance at the National School of Public Administration.
To break this deadlock, he suggested that Quebec City give a special mandate to the Auditor General to investigate collusion and corruption.
"We must be able to expand the mandate of the auditor general," he said.
He also believes that Quebec could give the auditor the same powers as a commissioner, allowing him to compel people to testify.
The creation of a permanent squad is not the only project in the Charest government's plans.
Quebec would also ask Ottawa to amend the Criminal Code to be better adapted to this type of crime.
This request would come from the prosecutor of Operation Marteau, who informed Justice Minister Jean-Marc Fournier that the jurisprudence is not explicit in this type of investigation.
Federal Public Safety Minister Vic Toews confirmed that his Justice colleague Rob Nicholson is currently considering some amendments related to the issue.
During Operation Spring 2001, which hit motorcycle groups, although the Criminal Code was not adequate, 131 people were arrested.
Ottawa subsequently passed the Gangsterism Act.
Rivers under close surveillance
Several rivers remain under close surveillance due to the heavy rainfall that has hit several regions of the province since Tuesday.
A landslide occurred Wednesday afternoon in Shawinigan, Mauricie.
Two houses were evacuated as a preventive measure.
In the evening, another slippage would have occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A road collapsed.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rainfall fell on several regions, with 40 to 70 millimeters of rain.
An additional 20 to 40 millimeters of rain was expected by Thursday evening, depending on the region.
Areas north of the river and in the Ottawa Valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to 100 millimeters of rain in total.
Since this precipitation must be added to the melting of snow already accumulated in some areas, there is concern that several rivers will overflow.
Flood warning warnings were issued Wednesday night by the Civil Security of Quebec for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers, in Lanaudière.
The North River, in Saint-Jérôme, in the Laurentians, and the Oak River, in Lotbinière, were subject to flood watches and remained under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region, heavy precipitation caused some lakes to overflow in Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
In Saint-Calixte, a temporary bridge was washed away due to heavy rains.
Ten residences had to be evacuated as a preventive measure.
In the Outaouais, the overflow of certain lakes has led to the closure of several roads, particularly in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
Civil Security remains on alert and is monitoring the situation closely, said Annik Bouchard, Security Advisor.
The Quebec Flood Prediction Centre issued heavy flood warnings Wednesday for several rivers, including Maskinongé, L'Assomption, Ouareau, Achigan, Batiscan and du Loup.
Dupont partially blamed
Quebec City radio host Stéphane Dupont suffered a partial setback before the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council (CBSC) for controversial comments about social assistance and Haitians as well as his coarse language on air.
The CBSC found that Mr. Dupont and his team at CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinions, but that some of the comments contained "inaccurate information on social assistance, unduly negative portrayals of Haitians and coarse language that is inappropriate for programs broadcast during the day."
The Commission also found that a discussion of suicide, including the broadcast of the names of two individuals who had committed suicide, did not violate the broadcasting codes.
The CBSC had received several complaints about comments made during programs broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was rendered following a complaint by the Front commun des personnes assistées sociales du Québec.
The group complained that the amounts quoted in the program were inaccurate.
Facilitators must present solid rather than misleading information.
Regarding suicide, the host Stéphane Dupont had estimated that suicide is a cowardly gesture.
The majority of Committee members concluded that the message was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life's problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the implicated episodes of 'Dupont le midi' addressed a sensitive subject in a fair and appropriate manner."
No blame was therefore placed on him.
