A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that is almost one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan comes on the heels of the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to reduce overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance still 5 Gt to stabilize by 2020 the rise of the climate at 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by two more times.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place guidelines.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent light bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in glowing bulbs.
In the U.S. alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make as a result of this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion to build.
