That of 2022 will be much more exotic, the International Federation hoping to conquer new territories (Qatar, Australia), after a first on the African continent in 2010, or continue its establishment in the United States or the Far East (Japan, South Korea).
The list of personalities who are part of the delegations (David Cameron, Prince William, José Luis Rodriguez Zapatero, José Socrates, Bill Clinton, the Emir of Qatar, the Belgian and Dutch heads of government, Zidane, Beckham, Cruyff) gives the measure of the economic and political stakes of a World Cup.
Behind-the-scenes negotiations are therefore likely to last until the last minute.
For the rest, it is difficult to establish a hierarchy between the candidates.
According to FIFA's evaluation report, the English, Spanish-Portuguese (2018) and American (2022) files have better arguments than their competitors.
But these considerations will not weigh very heavily on the 22 members of the executive committee at the time of the vote.
The Sunday Times, at the origin of the revelations that led to the suspension for corruption of two members of the EC (Reynald Temarii and Amos Adamu), could have ruined the chances of his country, cradle of football that has hosted the World Cup only once, in 1966.
The BBC put a layer back on Monday, broadcasting a documentary that pins three influential members of the EC, Ricardo Teixeira, Nicolas Leoz and Issa Hayatou.
Enough to displease FIFA and embarrass English officials, who have embarked on intense lobbying in recent weeks with David Cameron on the front line.
The head of government hopes to repeat the coup succeeded by his predecessor Tony Blair, who won the organisation of the 2012 Olympic Games for London in 2005.
Will this intense activity be enough to restore England's image with the EC?
Nothing is less certain because the Spain-Portugal duo does not lack assets with its stadiums already ready, its expertise (World-82 in Spain, Olympics-92 in Barcelona, Euro-2004 in Portugal) and its football culture.
But the gloomy economic and financial outlook for both countries could dampen their ambitions.
The possible retaliation against the English and doubts about the solvency of Spain and Portugal only increase the rating of Russia, which has become a major outsider despite the shortcomings of its file (stadiums, hotels, transport).
