Euro: ECB forced to maintain purchases of government securities
The last meeting of the Governing Council of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year was to be an opportunity to clarify the modalities for ending the crisis or, at least, to announce the cessation of many of the unconventional monetary policy operations due to end at the end of the year.
Due to the European sovereign debt crisis, the Frankfurt issuing institution will probably not be able to afford to be so peremptory or risk aggravating a more than tense situation today on the European bond markets.
The political cost would be all the higher.
Yesterday, during a press conference, French Finance Minister Christine Lagarde praised the ECB's active role in resolving the debt crisis in Europe.
It declined to comment on whether it believed the central bank should do more, for example by increasing its sovereign bond purchase program.
"I reserve my thoughts for my European partners (...)".
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing by the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the president of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, was not more divided about his intentions, simply indicating that the program of purchase of government securities on the secondary market "continued" and that "we will see what we decide" at the meeting on Thursday.
The only certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1%, its lowest historical level since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of Treasury bonds by the ECB doubled last week to nearly €1.35 billion.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have made new purchases of Irish and Portuguese securities yesterday.
In total, Eurosystem central banks have purchased €67 billion since May 2010.
Among market participants, there is no doubt about expectations of further buying (see page 29).
Economists also do not expect a noticeable change of course.
While lending operations of more than three months have already disappeared from the ECB's arsenal, the ECB still allocates unlimited liquidity on generous terms and for maturities ranging from one week to three months.
Economists now expect this arrangement to be extended by a few months.
"I can't imagine her changing her program in any significant way."
"Otherwise it would be taking the risk of provoking new tensions in the short term," said Michael Schubert, economist at Commerzbank.
"A gradual exit announced during the first quarter of 2011 seems more likely," said Norbert Bräms, an economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
In terms of its interventions in the public debt market, "the ECB should maintain a volume of purchases of these bonds to animate a sluggish market," adds Norbert Bräms.
Given the large exposures of European banks to euro area sovereign debt markets, the issuing institution has no choice but to maintain its presence in the market.
"It must at all costs replace the lack of investors on the market and act in such a way as to prevent a runaway yield paid by the most fragile states," said a major bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates soar, governments will be all the more embarrassed to reduce their debt, if not stabilize it.
The safeguarding of the euro is at this price.
