Snow and ice: 24 departments on orange alert
Snowy episodes still cause traffic difficulties, especially on the secondary network in Brittany, and may disrupt certain economic activities.
Twenty-four departments are now on orange alert because of the risk of snow and ice.
Eure, Eure-et-Loir, Deux-Sèvres and Vienne, were added to the 20 departments already on orange alert, 18 since Wednesday afternoon and two, Dordogne and Gironde, later in the night.
According to Météo France, sustained snow showers affect the north of the Gironde and the Charentes and it snows lightly on the Ile-de-France.
Snow layers ranging from 2 to 5 cm, occasionally from 7 to 10 cm, are expected for the departments concerned, and from 1 to 3 cm, or even up to 5 cm for the Paris region.
The departments concerned are those of Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d'Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, Poitou and those of the regions of Lower Normandy, Ile-de-France and Limousin.
Snowy episodes are notable enough to cause traffic difficulties and disrupt certain economic activities, warns Météo France.
In the Côtes d'Armor, several departmental roads have been banned for heavy goods vehicles over 7.5 tons, including the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac axes.
Traffic on the secondary network in Brittany is very difficult according to the gendarmes who recommend taking your vehicle only when necessary and the circulation of some TER buses has been suspended for the day.
School transport has been banned for Thursday in Picardy.
No specific measures were envisaged Wednesday evening to restrict the circulation of heavy goods vehicles.
The prefecture "invites all motorists to be very careful on the roads and to adapt their driving accordingly".
The Directorate General of Civil Aviation (DGAC) asked airlines to cancel Thursday 25% of their flights at Paris Roissy airport and 10% at Orly because of the upcoming snowfall.
The DGAC recommends that air passengers contact their airline.
