Avenging hackers and spys in stagecoach
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let us proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every dossier compiled by a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's eerily cartoonish profile has long been sketch material for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only consist of already known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what was already written in previous works.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know, and which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Ditto for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor of Liberation), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as that which Newsweek published the week before.
So why have the revelations about these cases caused so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since heads of state can telephone each other or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises in representation,  have turned into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating this publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to cast American diplomacy in the wrong light.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country is a significant blow to the State Department's prestige.
So the scandal does not put the victims in crisis so much as the "executioners".
But let us come to the deeper nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every move of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since that, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as is happening now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control ratio ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the vengeful citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the possibility of keeping its own secrets hold?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that everything you know about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to take away her power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but did too great a credit to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - this would be like publishing it on a poster stuck on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with today's technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I am well aware that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet re-established a wire (telephone) telegraph.
(Analog) videocassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now (digital) CDs only allow you to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macro portions.
With high-speed trains, you go from Rome to Milan in three hours, whereas by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that politics and communications technology should return to horse-drawn carriages.
One final observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secrecy of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how the France is tinkering with its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to review the fulfilment of the pledges of fast-release financing (so-called fast start or early-stage financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and the France €1.26 billion (€420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a big side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency exercise is valuable and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has made €2.2 billion available in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Accord, this money must be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some member states including the France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, the France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of France support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, like the France, consider that 1 € lent is equivalent to 1 € given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted as part of its commitments.
But the France does not care about such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% grants (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, the France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice sleight of hand!
In summary, in its fast-start financing, the France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small question, of relative short-term, compared to the whole climate discussion.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, the France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, the France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
The France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on the France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemical substances in one day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistically significant value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the food generally consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of the Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as treats, were examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet of the plate is damning: 81 chemical substances, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EDCs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear in our survey that the reality of consumer exposure to possibly carcinogenic contaminants and / or EDC is worrying," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances including a fungicide yet banned in France.
The same goes for green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a strong insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, ground steak, canned tuna, and even bread baguette and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water the analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even examining the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt from it.
The final risk to the consumer of this "cocktails of contaminants" "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Europe Ecology-Greens Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
